### PHP JSON Encoding and Decoding

PHP provides built-in functions for working with JSON data.

### json_encode

Converts PHP values to JSON format.

```php
<?php
$data = [
    "name" => "John",
    "age" => 30,
    "city" => "New York",
    "hobbies" => ["reading", "coding"]
];

$json = json_encode($data);
echo $json;
// {"name":"John","age":30,"city":"New York","hobbies":["reading","coding"]}
?>
```

### json_decode

Converts JSON string to PHP values.

```php
<?php
$json = '{"name":"John","age":30}';

// Decode to object
$obj = json_decode($json);
echo $obj->name; // John

// Decode to array (second parameter true)
$arr = json_decode($json, true);
echo $arr["name"]; // John
?>
```

### JSON Constants

| Constant | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `JSON_PRETTY_PRINT` | Format with whitespace |
| `JSON_UNESCAPED_UNICODE` | Don't escape Unicode |
| `JSON_UNESCAPED_SLASHES` | Don't escape `/` |
| `JSON_NUMERIC_CHECK` | Convert numeric strings to numbers |
| `JSON_FORCE_OBJECT` | Encode array as object |

### Pretty Print Example

```php
<?php
$data = ["name" => "Alice", "scores" => [95, 87, 92]];
echo json_encode($data, JSON_PRETTY_PRINT | JSON_UNESCAPED_UNICODE);
?>
```

### Error Handling

```php
<?php
$json = '{"invalid": json}';
$result = json_decode($json);

if (json_last_error() !== JSON_ERROR_NONE) {
    echo "JSON Error: " . json_last_error_msg();
}
?>
```

> **Key Point:** Use `json_decode($json, true)` to get an associative array instead of an object. Always check `json_last_error()` when decoding untrusted JSON.
